SIMPLE: embryo
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Embryo
<hw>Em"bry*o</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Embryos</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[F. <ets>embryon</ets>, Gr.
<grk>'e`mbryon</grk>, perh. fr. <?/ in (akin to L. <?/ E. <ets>in</ets>)
+ <?/ to be full of, swell with; perh. akin to E.
<ets>brew</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>The first rudiments of
an organism, whether animal or plant</def>; as: <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The
young of an animal in the womb, or more specifically, before its parts
are developed and it becomes a fetus (see <er>Fetus</er>).</def>
<sd>(b)</sd> <def>The germ of the plant, which is inclosed in the seed
and which is developed by germination.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>In embryo</b></col>, <cd>in an incipient or undeveloped
state; in conception, but not yet executed.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧The company
little suspected what a noble work I had then <xex>in
embryo</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Swift.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Embryo</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Embryo
<hw>Em"bry*o</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Pertaining to an embryo;
rudimentary; undeveloped; <as>as, an <ex>embryo</ex> bud</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Embryogenic</ent>⟦br⟧
